<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41014d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41014d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41014d"> 14(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> rattle &amp; gong</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I am not aware that there is any general history of the bell, beginning with <mark>the rattle, the gong</mark> and other primitive forms of the article; but the subject seems worthy of a monograph. In Hebrew Writ the bell first appears in Exod. xxviii. 33 as a fringe to the Ephod of the High Priest that its tinkling might save him from intruding unwarned into the bodily presence of the tribal God, Jehovah. <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RBTE3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE3"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) VII, 100n4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
